From f34916312e4ca20bdcd98e532239361cfe4e77c3 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Nadia Chambers <nadia.yvette.chambers@ik.me>
Date: Fri, 8 May 2026 20:31:37 +0200
Subject: [PATCH 100/174] arm64: contpte: preserve sub-page offset when folding
 CONT range

contpte_convert() reset the PTE via pfn_pte(pte_pfn(pte), prot), which
always points at sub-page 0 of the enclosing kernel page.  With PGCL, a
kernel page contains PAGE_MMUCOUNT sub-pages spanning several CONT_PTE
ranges (four ranges of 16 sub-PTEs at PGCL=6); resetting to sub-page 0
silently miscolored ranges 1/2/3 to map sub-pages 0..15 instead of
16..31, 32..47 and 48..63.  The cluster loop in do_anonymous_page
installs all 64 sub-PTEs in order, so contpte_try_fold succeeds for
each CONT range and contpte_convert quietly corrupted the higher
ranges' mappings -- reads at those virtual addresses then returned
data from the wrong sub-pages, almost always zeros for fresh stack
pages, making userspace ldp x29,x30,[sp,#16];ret jump to NULL.

Use ALIGN_DOWN(__pte_to_phys(pte), CONT_PTE_SIZE) so the rebuilt PTE
points at the first sub-page of *this* CONT range, matching the
expected_pte computation in __contpte_try_fold().

Fixes the cow_mprotect_race / cow_just_fork SEGVs reproduced as
pc=0/lr=0 on aarch64 PGCL=6.  Verified across five stability runs:
pgcl-test 19p/0f, pgcl-stress 12p/0f (cow_mprotect_race PASS), and
cow_just_fork 0/100 SEGVs per run (was ~2-3% per iter without the
fix).

Co-Authored-By: Claude Opus 4.7 <noreply@anthropic.com>
---
 arch/arm64/mm/contpte.c | 12 ++++++++----
 1 file changed, 8 insertions(+), 4 deletions(-)

diff --git a/arch/arm64/mm/contpte.c b/arch/arm64/mm/contpte.c
index eb6d1acdade7..94ce5e14e695 100644
--- a/arch/arm64/mm/contpte.c
+++ b/arch/arm64/mm/contpte.c
@@ -77,11 +77,15 @@ static void contpte_convert(struct mm_struct *mm, unsigned long addr,
 	start_ptep = ptep = contpte_align_down(ptep);
 	start_addr = addr = ALIGN_DOWN(addr, CONT_PTE_SIZE);
 	/*
-	 * With PGCL, pte_pfn() already returns PAGE-granular PFNs (sub-page
-	 * bits dropped), and one kernel page = one contpte block. So pfn_pte
-	 * with the raw pte_pfn gives sub-page 0 of the kernel page.
+	 * Reset the PTE to point at the FIRST sub-page of this CONT range
+	 * (which may not be sub-page 0 of the enclosing kernel page).  With
+	 * PGCL, a kernel page contains PAGE_MMUCOUNT sub-pages and several
+	 * CONT_PTE-sized cont ranges; using pfn_pte(pte_pfn(pte), ...) would
+	 * always reset to sub-page 0 of the kernel page, miscoloring the
+	 * second/third/fourth cont range to point back at sub-page 0.
 	 */
-	pte = pfn_pte(pte_pfn(pte), pte_pgprot(pte));
+	pte = __pte(__phys_to_pte_val(ALIGN_DOWN(__pte_to_phys(pte),
+				CONT_PTE_SIZE)) | pgprot_val(pte_pgprot(pte)));
 
 	for (i = 0; i < CONT_PTES; i++, ptep++, addr += MMUPAGE_SIZE) {
 		pte_t ptent = __ptep_get_and_clear(mm, addr, ptep);
-- 
